---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import CodeCard from '../components/CodeCard.astro';

// Story 1 - a dapp backend. Multi-contract init works today; Arbitrum and
// non-Transfer decode are design targets (this page is a design preview).
const initCmd = `nuthatch init --chain arbitrum-one \\
  0x1F98431c8aD98523631AE4a59f267346ea31F984 \\
  0xC36442b4a4522E871399CD717aBDD847Ab11FE88`;

const positionsView = `create view positions as
select user_address,
       sum(case when kind = 'deposit'  then amount else 0 end)
       - sum(case when kind = 'withdraw' then amount else 0 end) as net_supplied
from (
  select user_address, amount, 'deposit'  as kind from deposit
  union all
  select user_address, amount, 'withdraw' as kind from withdraw
)
group by user_address;`;

const sqlCurl = `curl -s http://127.0.0.1:8288/sql \\
  -H 'content-type: application/json' \\
  -d '{"query": "select net_supplied from positions where user_address = $1", "params": ["0x7a250d5630B4cF539739dF2C5dAcb4c659F2488D"]}'`;

// Story 2 - a published nest. init --from is a design target.
const initFrom = `nuthatch init --from https://github.com/nuthatch-indexer/horizon-nest`;

const indexersQuery = `select * from indexers order by total_rewards_earned desc limit 20;`;

// Story 3 - a local agent. The MCP server and its schema/sql tools work today.
const mcpConfig = `{
  "mcpServers": {
    "nuthatch": { "command": "nuthatch", "args": ["mcp"] }
  }
}`;
---
<Layout
  path="/stories"
  title="Who runs Nuthatch - Nuthatch"
  description="Three workflows through Nuthatch's three front doors: an SQL endpoint for app backends, published nests for analysts, and a built-in MCP server for agents. Illustrative personas, running on v0.5.0; a GraphQL compatibility layer is the main piece still on the roadmap."
>
  <section class="page">
    <article class="wrap narrow prose">
      <p class="section-label">Stories</p>
      <h1>Who runs Nuthatch</h1>

      <p>
        Nuthatch has three front doors: an SQL endpoint for application backends, published
        nests for people who want data without writing indexing code, and a built-in MCP
        server for agents. Same binary, same data, one process on your own hardware.
      </p>
      <p class="illus">Illustrative workflows, not customer stories - Nuthatch is early v0.5.0 software.</p>

      <p class="preview-note">
        <strong>These workflows run on v0.5.0.</strong> Multi-contract nests, every declared event
        as a queryable table, Arbitrum One and Base, user-authored <code>views/*.sql</code>,
        <code>init --from</code>, read-only <code>/sql</code>, and the MCP server all ship today - as
        do factories, the compliance pack, the admin UI, and webhooks. The main forward-looking piece
        for these stories is the GraphQL layer, noted where it appears; the personas are
        illustrative. See the <a href="/roadmap">roadmap</a> for the dividing line.
      </p>

      <div class="in-production">
        <h2>Live in production: Lodestar</h2>
        <p>
          Not illustrative - this one is real. <a href="https://www.lodestar-dashboard.com" rel="noopener">Lodestar</a>,
          an analytics dashboard for The Graph Protocol on Arbitrum One, serves two of its panels
          from a single nuthatch binary on one small box instead of The Graph gateway. The
          <strong>Delegation Activity</strong> feed (HorizonStaking delegation events) comes through
          byte-for-byte identical to the subgraph; the <strong>Developer Activity</strong> chart
          (L2GNS subgraph publishes) tracks it within a documented ~0-1%. Both run flag-gated, with
          automatic fallback to the old gateway - two panels that no longer depend on a third-party
          data API.
        </p>
        <p class="prod-box">
          The box: two nests, backfilled and serving live, in <strong>86 MB of RAM</strong> on one
          Hetzner VPS - Caddy for TLS, path-routed to one URL. The footprint budget is 2 GB.
          <a href="/blog/serving-lodestar-from-one-box">The full write-up is on the blog.</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- STORY 1 -->
      <h2>A dapp backend</h2>
      <p>
        Maya's three-person team runs a lending protocol on Arbitrum. The frontend needs user
        positions, borrow history, and a few protocol-wide stats - the read side of the app,
        the part a managed indexer usually bills for.
      </p>
      <p>
        She points one command at the protocol's contracts and runs it on a €15 VPS. Nothing
        else to provision: no Postgres, no queue, no second box.
      </p>
      <CodeCard code={initCmd} lang="bash" label="one init, every contract" />
      <p>
        Every event in those ABIs becomes a queryable table as the backfill streams through
        history, so she can read the raw layer before modelling anything. The positions her
        frontend needs are one declarative view over deposits and withdrawals:
      </p>
      <CodeCard code={positionsView} lang="sql" label="views/positions.sql" />
      <p>
        Her API route calls <code>POST /sql</code> the same way it would call Postgres - one
        read-only endpoint on localhost, no driver to install, no connection pool to babysit:
      </p>
      <CodeCard code={sqlCurl} lang="bash" label="the frontend reads it like a database" />
      <p>
        When Arbitrum reorgs, the affected rows retract and anything derived from them corrects
        itself; the frontend never sees the wobble.
      </p>
      <p>
        What she stopped doing: paying per entity for her own application's data, and trusting a
        third party's uptime for a read path she now runs herself.
      </p>

      <hr class="divider seg" />

      <!-- STORY 2 -->
      <h2>A dashboard, no indexing code</h2>
      <p>
        Petar delegates GRT and wants one thing: to see which Graph Horizon indexers actually
        earn. He does not want to write handlers, and he does not need to.
      </p>
      <p>
        He pulls a published nest - the
        <a href="https://github.com/nuthatch-indexer/horizon-nest" rel="noopener">horizon-nest</a>,
        with contracts, vendored ABIs, and derived views all included - and runs it against his own
        node. He wrote no indexing code; he ran someone else's definition:
      </p>
      <CodeCard code={initFrom} lang="bash" label="run a published nest" />
      <p>
        From there the data is just SQL. One query drives a Grafana panel, or a bare HTML page
        with a single <code>fetch</code>:
      </p>
      <CodeCard code={indexersQuery} lang="sql" label="via /sql" />
      <p>
        The point is that a nest is a shareable indexing <em>definition</em>, not a hosted feed:
        he ran it on his own hardware and can read every line of what produced the numbers.
      </p>
      <p class="note">
        Derived views read finalized data; the raw event tables are fresh to the tip. A
        dashboard built on views trails the chain head by finality - the honest trade for
        numbers that never retract under you.
      </p>

      <hr class="divider seg" />

      <!-- STORY 3 -->
      <h2>An agent, locally</h2>
      <p>
        Dana builds a DeFi assistant. She wants it to answer questions about on-chain data
        without shipping that data - or her users' questions - to anyone.
      </p>
      <p>She adds Nuthatch to the agent's MCP config. That is the whole integration:</p>
      <CodeCard code={mcpConfig} lang="json" label=".mcp.json" />
      <p>
        The agent discovers the schema itself through the <code>schema</code> tool and composes
        queries through the <code>sql</code> tool, so when her user types "which indexers grew
        delegation fastest this month?" it writes the query rather than guessing the shape.
      </p>
      <p>
        Nothing leaves the machine: no API key, no per-query bill, and it works offline against
        the local instance.
      </p>

      <hr class="divider close-div" />
      <p class="signoff">
        The pattern across all three: nobody deployed to someone else's platform, nobody got an
        API key, and nobody's story ends with a monthly invoice. To a frontend, Nuthatch looks
        like a fast read-only database that fills itself from the chain and heals itself through
        reorgs. GraphQL is on the roadmap for subgraph-shaped clients.
      </p>
      <p class="storylinks">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/install">Try the quickstart</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/example">See the full example</a>
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .page { padding-block: clamp(3rem, 6vw, 4.5rem) clamp(4rem, 9vw, 6.5rem); }
  .prose h1 { margin-bottom: 1.4rem; line-height: 1.12; }
  .prose h2 { margin-top: 2.6rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 1.5rem; }
  .prose p { color: var(--text-muted); font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.72; margin-bottom: 1.3rem; }
  .prose p:first-of-type { color: var(--text); }
  .illus { font-size: 0.9rem !important; color: var(--text-faint) !important; margin-top: -0.4rem; }
  .preview-note {
    background: var(--pale-rust-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--rust); border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: 1rem 1.2rem; font-size: 0.95rem !important; color: var(--text-muted) !important;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  .preview-note strong { color: var(--text); }
  .in-production {
    background: var(--pale-rust-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent, #6aa84f); border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: 0.4rem 1.2rem 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0 2rem;
  }
  .in-production h2 { margin-top: 0.8rem; }
  .in-production p { color: var(--text-muted); margin-bottom: 0; }
  .in-production .prod-box { margin-top: 1rem; font-size: 0.95rem; color: var(--text-faint); }
  .in-production strong { color: var(--text); }
  .prose :global(.codecard) { margin-bottom: 1.4rem; }
  .note { font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--text-faint); }
  .seg { margin-block: 2.6rem; }
  .close-div { margin-block: 2.6rem 1.8rem; }
  .signoff { color: var(--text) !important; }
  .storylinks { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.75rem; margin-top: 0.4rem; }
</style>
</content>
</invoke>
